Object-oriented programming (OOP) is a programming language model organized around objects, or instances of data within data structures, rather than actions and logic. As an object-oriented programming language, OOP focuses on the creation, manipulation, and usage of objects to create programs, rather than a sequence of processes or instructions. OOP is commonly used for applications where the focus is on an object, such as art, music, or games, for example. A main feature of OOP is the use of composition or inheritance to reuse the code, which saves the programmer valuable time as they don't have to keep rewriting code to use different objects.

In an OOP language, syntax is based around classes and objects. For example, in Java, it would be class Car {private String name;}, which instantiates an object with the class Car, and its attributes of a string name. Semantic meaning in OOP is based around relationships. For example, the Car class contains the method getName() which will return the string name of the object Car. Design principles used in OOP are encapsulation, where the data and behavior of an object is combined and hidden from outside users, and inheritance, which allows the objects to inherit and extend the features of other objects or classes.

Procedural programming is a programming language model that is organized around procedures, or sequences of instructions, rather than objects. Syntax wise, procedural programming relies heavily on while, if then, switch, and other loop statements. Semantic in procedural programming is usually focused on function calls, and how the order in which the functions are called affects the outcomes. Design principles used in procedural programming are abstraction, which hides the code details from the outside user, and modularization, which allows the code to be broken up into logical units to reduce complexity. 

An example of code written in procedural programming would be:

```
// define functions 
int sum(int a, int b){
    return a + b;
}

int difference(int a, int b){
    return a - b;
}

// use them in a main function
int main(){
    // variables
