    int b = 5;  

    // print results
    printf("Sum: %d\n", sum(a,b));
    printf("Difference: %d\n", difference(a,b));

   return 0;
}
```

Object-oriented programming differs from procedural programming in a variety of ways. OOP focuses on objects, and procedural programming focuses on functions or procedures. Additionally, OOP uses design principles such as inheritance and encapsulation, while procedural programming relies on abstraction and modularization. Finally, OOP syntax is based around classes and objects, while procedural syntax is based around while, if then, switch, and other loop statements.

