Procedural Programming (PP) is a programming paradigm that utilizes a step-by-step approach to programming, with no data objects being employed. In PP, instructions are given in the form of function calls which work together as a sequence of instructions to impose the corresponding tasks.

The main difference between OOP and PP lies in their syntax, semantics, and design principles. OOP code emphasizes data-abstraction principles, creating objects out of the data, and leveraging specialization through the use of data members and methods. Whereas PP focuses on the sequence of instructions, defining a set of steps underpinned by clever looping and conditionals, instead of constructing objects and relationships.

