Bubble Sort: 
Bubble sort is a simple sorting algorithm that compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are out of order. It is inefficient in its implementation and has a time complexity of O(n2). Bubble Sort requires a single extra memory space to operate and has a space complexity of O(1).

// C++ code example for Bubble Sort
void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) 
{  
    int i, j; 
    for (i = 0; i < n-1; i++)       
        for (j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++)  
            if (arr[j] > arr[j+1]) 
                swap(&arr[j], &arr[j+1]); 
} 

Insertion Sort: 
Insertion sort is a sorting algorithm that builds the final sorted array, one element at a time. It is fast for small inputs but inefficient for large data sets. Insertion sort has a time complexity of O(n2) and a space complexity of O(1).

// C++ code example for Insertion Sort
void insertionSort(int arr[], int n) 
{ 
    int i, key, j; 
    for (i = 1; i < n; i++) { 
        key = arr[i]; 
        j = i - 1; 

        while (j >= 0 && arr[j] > key) { 
            arr[j + 1] = arr[j]; 
            j = j - 1; 
        } 
        arr[j + 1] = key; 
    } 
} 

Selection Sort:
Selection Sort is a sorting algorithm that systematically searches for the smallest or the largest element in the array and places it in its correct position. It is an inefficient form of sorting and has a time complexity of O(n2). It has a space complexity of O(1).

// C++ code example for Selection Sort
void selectionSort(int arr[], int n) 
{ 
    int i, j, min_idx; 

    for (i = 0; i < n-1; i++) 
    { 
        min_idx = i; 
        for (j = i+1; j < n; j++) 
